{"title_page": "Qubad Talabani", "text_new": "{{void}}{{Infobox State Representative\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Qubad Talabani\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =Qubad Talabani Photo.jpg\n| state_assembly = [[Kurdish National Assembly]]\n| term_start = June 2014 \n| term_end =\n| office = Deputy Prime Minister of Kurdistan Region Government\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Iraqi of Kurdish descent\n| party = [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]]\n| residence = [[Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n| alma_mater =\n| religion = \n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n|father=[[Jalal Talabani]]\n|mother=Hero Ibrahim Ahmad\n}}\n\n'''Qubad Talabani''' (born 21 July 1977) is an Iraqi Kurdish politician who has been  the Deputy Prime Minister of the [[Kurdistan Region]] since 2014. Formerly serving as the representative of Kurdistan to the [[United States]], Qubad is the second son of Iraqi former President [[Jalal Talabani]].\n\n== Early life ==\nDeputy Prime Minister Talabani was born in 1977 and grew up in [[Surrey]], [[United Kingdom]] with his maternal grandparents, [[Ibrahim Ahmed]], a novelist, poet and a founder of the modern intellectual [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]] movement and Galawejh Ahmed (also a novelist). His family has been involved in Kurdish politics for decades; His father, [[Jalal Talabani]], was the President of the [[Republic of Iraq]] from 2006 until 2014. \n\nAfter graduating from High School, he obtained a Diploma in Motor Vehicle Engineering at [[Carshalton College]], and later received a degree in Mechanical Engineering at the [[Kingston University]] in London.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gov.krd/english/government/deputy-prime-minister/|title=Qubad Talabani|website=Kurdistan Regional Government|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nFrom 2001 to 2003, Qubad worked as a special assistant to  [[Barham Salih]], at that time the Representative of the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] (one of Iraq's leading Kurdish political parties) in Washington D.C., and later as the Deputy PUK Representative.<ref name=huff/> In 2003, he returned to [[Kurdistan]] for one year and served as the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan|PUK]]'s Senior Foreign Relations officer to the coalition forces and the Coalition Provisional Authority. He also acted as a liaison officer between the PUK and U.S. military forces in [[Iraq]].<ref>[http://www.jmu.edu/jmuweb/general/news/general6403.shtml IRAQI PRESIDENT'S SON TO SPEAK ON IRAQ'S FUTURE]</ref> He was a leading negotiator in the drafting of the Transitional Administrative Law (TAL), the first Iraqi constitution since the overthrow of [[Saddam Hussein]].<ref name=huff>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/qubad-j-talabani ''The Huffington Post'']</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Qubad returned to the US, and was stationed as the Representative of the PUK and Kurdistan.\n\nIn 2006, with the unification of the two administrations in [[Kurdistan]] and following the forming of the [[Democratic Patriotic Alliance of Kurdistan]] and the establishment of the [[Kurdish National Assembly]],<ref>[http://www2.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0706.rozen.html The Scion Kurdistan's man in Washington By Laura Rozen]</ref> Qubad was appointed as the first representative of the Kurdistan Region, a position he has held until 2012<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2014 he was nominated Deputy Prime Minister of the Government of the Kurdistan region and was involved in the implementation of the biometric registration system for government employees.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nHe was first sworn in as Deputy Prime Minister of the KRG Cabinet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.gov.krd/en/nechirvan-barzani-praises-the-eighth-government-cabinet/|title=Nechirvan Barzani Commends the 8th Cabinet of the Kurdistan Regional Government|date=2019-07-06|website=President of the Kurdistan Region of Iraq|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> in June 2014, where he took office. Receiving no fiscal transfers from the [[Government of Iraq]] (GoI), coupled with rapidly declining oil prices, the Kurdistan region was in the midst of a severe financial crisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/a38b70a2-e39c-45d4-94e6-d5f3a3eef2ab/KRG-alone-in-solving-financial-crisis|title=KRG alone in solving financial crisis|last=Kurdistan24|website=Kurdistan24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>. Moreover, the [[Islamic State of Iraq|Islamic State]] was rampaging its way throughout Iraq, claiming territory and establishing itself as one of history\u2019s most brutal terrorist organizations, resulting in a major humanitarian crisis that forced 1.8 million people to flee war and violence and seek refuge in the Kurdistan region<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/06/iraqis-seek-refuge-kurdish-north-20146217557290137.html Iraqis seeks refuge in Kurdish north]</ref>. During this period, the KRG successfully oversaw a package of reforms. \n\nA major part of the KRG\u2019s economic reform plan included improving oversight of government expenditures. To that end, Talabani successfully oversaw the design and implementation of his government\u2019s biometric registration program.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nDuring the KRG\u2019s Seventh Cabinet, Talabani established and headed up the Department of Coordination and Follow-up to facilitate inter-ministerial coordination. He directed that KRG agency on behalf of the Prime Minister for two years.\n\nIn the parliamentary elections of the Kurdistan region of 2018<ref name=\":0\" /> he was elected to parliament but he did not assume his post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/54d4104c-931e-42f4-88a6-c0ded133c936|title=Qubad Talabani, two other MPs relinquish seats in Kurdistan parliament|last=Kurdistan24|website=Kurdistan24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>    \n\nQubad Talabani appears frequently on major television networks and in the press where he discusses Iraqi and Kurdistan issues.<ref name=huff/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeputy Prime Minister Talabani is the son of [[Jalal Talabani]] and [[Hero Ibrahim Ahmed]] and the younger brother of PUK political figure [[Bafel Talabani]]. He lives in [[Erbil]] with his wife [[Sherri Kraham]] whom he married in Il Castello del Palagio in Italy in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212094457/http://www.chianticlassico.com/english/magazine/200505/articolo0.asp|title=DIPLOMATIC WEDDING IN CHIANTI - Chianti Classico Magazine|date=2008-02-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> and their two children, Ari and Lara. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160204145003/http://qubadsblog.com/ Qubad Talabani's blog]\n* [http://www.sourcewatch.org/index.php?title=Qubad_Talabani Profile] at [[SourceWatch]]\n*{{C-SPAN|Qubad Talabani}}\n* [[List of presidents of Iraq]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Talabani, Qubad}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Kingston University]]\n[[Category:Patriotic Union of Kurdistan politicians]]\n[[Category:Children of national leaders]]\n[[Category:Kurdish politicians]]\n[[Category:Government of Kurdistan Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{void}}{{Infobox State Representative\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Qubad Talabani\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =Qubad Talabani Photo.jpg\n| state_assembly = [[Kurdish National Assembly]]\n| term_start = June 2014 \n| term_end =\n| office = Deputy Prime Minister of Kurdistan Region Government\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Iraqi of Kurdish descent\n| party = [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]]\n| residence = [[Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n| alma_mater =\n| religion = \n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n|father=[[Jalal Talabani]]\n|mother=Hero Ibrahim Ahmad\n}}\n\n'''Qubad Ta